No box on these two jobs.

62
00:04:08,677 --> 00:04:10,152
Had to go to Missing Persons.

63
00:04:10,152 --> 00:04:14,155
A white woman and black man 
disappeared together June 3, 1969.

64
00:04:14,155 --> 00:04:16,227
Missing persons didn't 
knock themselves out.

65
00:04:16,227 --> 00:04:18,915
If you're over 18 and of sound mind,
you're allowed to disappeared.

66
00:04:18,915 --> 00:04:20,093
And the lifesyle.

67
00:04:20,093 --> 00:04:21,861
A lot of people disappeared 
in the '60s.

68
00:04:21,861 --> 00:04:23,226
Some of 'em don't even know it.

69
00:04:23,226 --> 00:04:26,210
The woman was Julia Hoffman, 22,

70
00:04:26,210 --> 00:04:29,060
reported missing by her 
parents, now deceased.

71
00:04:29,060 --> 00:04:30,656
Lived in a commune.

72
00:04:30,656 --> 00:04:34,096
Disappeared with Gerard Gary, 23.

73
00:04:34,096 --> 00:04:36,355
Looks like Julia's station 
wagon disappeared, too.

74
00:04:36,355 --> 00:04:37,669
We ran an NCIC search,

75
00:04:37,669 --> 00:04:39,799
see if the car ever turned 
up anywhere, but no luck.

76
00:04:39,799 --> 00:04:43,115
These bodies were dumped professional
style in that construction site.

77
00:04:43,115 --> 00:04:44,675
Which says organized crime.

78
00:04:44,675 --> 00:04:46,834
So how does that intersect
with hippies?

79
00:04:46,834 --> 00:04:48,019
Drugs?

80
00:04:48,019 --> 00:04:49,087
Had to buy them somewhere.

81
00:04:49,087 --> 00:04:51,094
Maybe the black-white 
thing bothered somebody.

82
00:04:51,094 --> 00:04:52,688
You got any family contacts 
on either of them?

83
00:04:52,688 --> 00:04:55,448
No, but we have a name 
on a boyfriend for Julia.

84
00:04:55,448 --> 00:04:56,676
Another commune member.

85
00:04:56,676 --> 00:04:58,833
You mean the guy she was 
found with wasn't her boyfriend?

86
00:04:58,833 --> 00:05:00,423
If he was, she had one at home, too.

87
00:05:00,423 --> 00:05:02,568
Not a bad motive for 
boyfriend Number One,

88
00:05:02,568 --> 00:05:03,977
there being a Number two.

89
00:05:03,977 --> 00:05:06,598
Let's go see this commune guy.

90
00:05:07,544 --> 00:05:12,552
Adam Clarke, where are you now?

91
00:05:14,557 --> 00:05:16,742
Life coach.

92
00:05:17,653 --> 00:05:20,212
You get to choose...

93
00:05:20,212 --> 00:05:23,200
how to view your experience.

94
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:25,376
What's the empowering choice?

95
00:05:25,376 --> 00:05:26,984
Taking responsibility.

96
00:05:26,984 --> 00:05:31,769
Winners take responsibility, all right?

97
00:05:31,769 --> 00:05:33,343
All right. See everyone tomorrow.

98
00:05:33,343 --> 00:05:35,129
Thanks.

99
00:05:35,129 --> 00:05:36,282
Adam Clarke?

100
00:05:36,282 --> 00:05:37,584
Yeah.

101
00:05:37,584 --> 00:05:41,971
Detective Rush and Valens, Homicide.

102
00:05:42,235 --> 00:05:44,036
That's a room-emptier.

103
00:05:44,036 --> 00:05:46,339
We're here about Julia Hoffman.

104
00:05:46,942 --> 00:05:49,863
You were dating her in 1969?

105
00:05:49,863 --> 00:05:51,247
Yeah.

106
00:05:51,542 --> 00:05:54,458
Till she disappeared on me.

107
00:05:55,474 --> 00:05:57,344
Her remains have been found.

108
00:05:57,344 --> 00:06:01,522
Along with the remains of Gerard Gary.

109
00:06:06,831 --> 00:06:08,486
You mind?

110
00:06:08,948 --> 00:06:11,289
They're herbal.

111
00:06:12,669 --> 00:06:16,384
I thought Julia went to Canada 
with that Gerard guy.

112
00:06:16,384 --> 00:06:18,739
Looks like they never 
made it out of the city.

113
00:06:18,739 --> 00:06:20,229
Ugly.

114
00:06:20,229 --> 00:06:22,333
What kind of relationship 
did you two have?

115
00:06:22,333 --> 00:06:25,827
Six months of hot and 
heavy in the commune.

116
00:06:25,827 --> 00:06:27,413
Serious?

117
00:06:27,413 --> 00:06:30,942
No. I was more serious 
about ending the war.

118
00:06:30,942 --> 00:06:34,321
So her being with this other 
guy didn't rile you at all.

119
00:06:34,321 --> 00:06:36,647
We had an open relationship.

120
00:06:37,135 --> 00:06:38,516
It was the '60s.

121
00:06:38,516 --> 00:06:39,995
It was part of the revolution--

122
00:06:39,995 --> 00:06:42,568
change the world, 
change ourselves.

123
00:06:42,568 --> 00:06:46,697
But human nature doesn't always
conform to revolutionary ideals.

124
00:06:46,697 --> 00:06:48,451
Well, that's why I do this work.

125
00:06:48,451 --> 00:06:51,390
And that's being a life coach, 
I take it.

126
00:06:51,390 --> 00:06:53,469
It's easy to make fun of.

127
00:06:53,469 --> 00:06:55,149
We have a saying:

128
00:06:55,149 --> 00:06:57,540
"Being cynical's the booby prize."

129
00:06:57,540 --> 00:07:00,451
Any idea if Julia and Gerard 
were dealing drugs?

130
00:07:00,451 --> 00:07:01,325
No chance.

131
00:07:01,325 --> 00:07:03,408
Aw, come on, Adam -- summer of '69.

132
00:07:03,408 --> 00:07:06,428
Oh, we took drugs, 
for sure, but... dealing?

133
00:07:06,428 --> 00:07:08,197
We just weren't that organized.

134
00:07:08,197 --> 00:07:13,465
The last time you saw Julia, did 
you fight, and part on bad terms?

135
00:07:13,465 --> 00:07:15,554
Furthest thing from it.

136
00:07:31,114 --> 00:07:32,888
It's time.

137
00:07:43,186 --> 00:07:46,743
Our soldiers are coming 
home in body bags!

138
00:07:46,743 --> 00:07:50,349
The Vietnamese people die and die!

139
00:07:50,616 --> 00:07:54,265
Now, there comes a time when you 
have to throw yourself into history,

140
00:07:54,265 --> 00:07:57,949
not stand on the sidelines.

141
00:07:59,496 --> 00:08:02,024
My draft card!

142
00:08:05,165 --> 00:08:07,681
You let'em arrest me!

143
00:08:08,362 --> 00:08:11,416
I'm saying no!

144
00:08:11,958 --> 00:08:14,918
I'm saying hell, no!

145
00:08:15,661 --> 00:08:19,974
I... won't... go!

146
00:08:22,268 --> 00:08:24,582
Hell, no, we won't go!

147
00:08:24,582 --> 00:08:26,899
Hell, no, we won't go!

148
00:08:26,899 --> 00:08:29,104
Hell, no, we won't go!

149
00:08:29,104 --> 00:08:31,100
Hell, no, we won't go!

150
00:08:31,100 --> 00:08:32,977
Hell, no, we won't go!

151
00:08:32,977 --> 00:08:34,908
Hell, no, we won't go!

152
00:08:34,908 --> 00:08:37,677
Hell, no, we won't go!

153
00:08:37,677 --> 00:08:39,363
Glory days, huh?

154
00:08:39,363 --> 00:08:42,931
Intense...
as we used to say.

155
00:08:42,931 --> 00:08:44,644
And Julia and Gerard being together,

156
00:08:44,644 --> 00:08:49,641
that didn't bring up any intense
feelings, like jealousy?

157
00:08:49,641 --> 00:08:51,808
It hurt, some.

158
00:08:52,125 --> 00:08:54,653
But that was our deal.

159
00:08:54,653 --> 00:08:56,506
Who was the girl with Julia?

160
00:08:56,506 --> 00:08:58,296
Her friend Terri.

161
00:08:58,296 --> 00:09:00,318
She lived with us for awhile.

162
00:09:00,318 --> 00:09:01,579
Remember her last name?

163
00:09:01,579 --> 00:09:02,955
Maxwell.

164
00:09:02,955 --> 00:09:06,576
A rich Cherry Hill girl who came and 
played hippie for a couple of years.

165
00:09:06,576 --> 00:09:09,268
Now she's a rich art dealer.

166
00:09:14,539 --> 00:09:18,573
Julia and I were on dishes 
duty at the commune.

167
00:09:18,573 --> 00:09:23,728
The men were totally into equality
until we ran out of clean plates.

168
00:09:25,205 --> 00:09:27,197
So you knew Adam Clarke?

169
00:09:27,197 --> 00:09:30,103
Of course! He was the 
king of the commune.

170
00:09:30,103 --> 00:09:33,655
Well, he claims he didn't mind 
Julia being with Gerard.

171
00:09:33,655 --> 00:09:34,938
You believe that?

172
00:09:34,938 --> 00:09:37,023
I do, actually.

173
00:09:37,385 --> 00:09:41,079
Only because he was 
so... self-absorbed.

174
00:09:41,079 --> 00:09:42,092
How so?

175
00:09:42,092 --> 00:09:44,677
He was the star of the 
anti-war movement.

176
00:09:44,677 --> 00:09:47,990
And he was inspiring, I admit.

177
00:09:47,990 --> 00:09:49,676
But he was an ass.

178
00:09:49,676 --> 00:09:53,127
He thought of himself as 
a babe magnet, '60s-style.

179
00:09:53,127 --> 00:09:55,613
Well, even babe magnets 
don't like being dumped.

180
00:09:55,613 --> 00:09:57,394
Especially babe magnets.

181
00:09:57,394 --> 00:10:01,240
I just don't think he cared 
enough about Julia to harm her.

182
00:10:01,240 --> 00:10:03,219
Right.

183
00:10:04,615 --> 00:10:07,803
There is something I didn't 
tell the police in '69.

184
00:10:07,803 --> 00:10:10,628
In my world, back then...

185
00:10:11,072 --> 00:10:13,278
you just didn't tell the 
cops a lot of things.

186
00:10:13,278 --> 00:10:14,900
Oink, oink?

187
00:10:14,900 --> 00:10:16,874
Yeah.

188
00:10:17,350 --> 00:10:19,777
What didn't you tell?

189
00:10:19,777 --> 00:10:25,848
Julia and Gerard were into 
something... clandestine.

190
00:10:25,848 --> 00:10:27,007
Like what?

191
00:10:27,007 --> 00:10:30,381
There were a lot of 
secret phone calls...

192
00:10:30,381 --> 00:10:35,026
um, messages from someone 
who called himself Dr.L.

193
00:10:35,026 --> 00:10:38,892
And Julia always had 
these envelopes of cash.

194
00:10:38,892 --> 00:10:40,921
And how do you know 
Gerard was involved?

195
00:10:40,921 --> 00:10:43,609
The night before they disappeared,

196
00:10:43,609 --> 00:10:45,612
they were planning something.

197
00:10:45,612 --> 00:10:47,183
Hell, no, we won't go!

198
00:10:47,183 --> 00:10:49,293
Hell, no, we won't go!

199
00:10:49,293 --> 00:10:51,302
The meeting place 
doesn't work anymore.

200
00:10:51,302 --> 00:10:52,784
I know.

201
00:10:52,784 --> 00:10:57,328
7:00 a.m. tomorrow, 
we pick up on a new corner.

202
00:10:57,328 --> 00:10:58,769
She'll have the bread?

203
00:10:58,769 --> 00:11:00,210
Yep.

204
00:11:01,218 --> 00:11:03,398
You scared?

205
00:11:04,399 --> 00:11:07,907
No way, baby. You?

206
00:11:10,285 --> 00:11:12,468
Hell, no, we won't go!

207
00:11:12,468 --> 00:11:14,774
Does he know?

208
00:11:16,149 --> 00:11:18,765
I'd never tell him.

209
00:11:33,341 --> 00:11:36,122
Julia was your best friend, and 
you didn't ask her what was up?

210
00:11:36,122 --> 00:11:38,133
She didn't wanna tell me.

211
00:11:38,133 --> 00:11:42,149
And to be honest,
I was scared to know.

212
00:11:42,443 --> 00:11:45,599
I was a suburbs girl trying 
out the commune life.

213
00:11:45,599 --> 00:11:49,922
If it ever got too gritty, 
I knew I could always go home.

214
00:11:49,922 --> 00:11:53,963
But Julia, she was for real,

215
00:11:53,963 --> 00:11:59,129
and she was into something... deep.

216
00:11:59,701 --> 00:12:01,933
Forensics found a long 
brown hair with the bodies

217
00:12:01,933 --> 00:12:03,617
under a piece of tape
on the plastic.

218
00:12:03,617 --> 00:12:04,859
Could be Julia's.

219
00:12:04,859 --> 00:12:06,513
We'll catch a break if it's not.

220
00:12:06,513 --> 00:12:07,827
Any leads on the missing car?

221
00:12:07,827 --> 00:12:09,768
Mm. Sludge.

222
00:12:09,768 --> 00:12:10,894
What about it?

223
00:12:10,894 --> 00:12:12,852
Uh, it was smeared on 
the plastic and the clothes,

224
00:12:12,852 --> 00:12:15,572
and has caffeic acid
and pyrazine in it.

225
00:12:15,572 --> 00:12:17,744
Chemicals made in 
manufacturing coffee.

226
00:12:17,744 --> 00:12:19,414
Killer gave'em one last cappuccino?

227
00:12:19,414 --> 00:12:21,300
Or they were wrapped 
up near the waterfront

228
00:12:21,300 --> 00:12:22,868
by the Bogata Coffee plant.

229
00:12:22,868 --> 00:12:24,215
Was it there in '69?

230
00:12:24,215 --> 00:12:25,959
Established '66.

231
00:12:25,959 --> 00:12:26,832
Smart, Nicky.

232
00:12:26,832 --> 00:12:29,542
Gives a specific place to 
dredge for a station wagon.

233
00:12:29,542 --> 00:12:30,922
That enough to get the divers out?

234
00:12:30,922 --> 00:12:33,307
I'll call the Marine Unit.

235
00:12:41,043 --> 00:12:42,812
I was at Woodstock, you know.

236
00:12:42,812 --> 00:12:44,046
You?

237
00:12:44,046 --> 00:12:46,812
Jimi Hendrix. That cat could play.

238
00:12:46,812 --> 00:12:48,234
Did he say "cat"?

239
00:12:48,234 --> 00:12:50,691
You take your clothes off 
and roll in the mud, boss?

240
00:12:50,691 --> 00:12:54,097
Uh, set-up and security
for one of the vendors.

241
00:12:54,097 --> 00:12:55,733
Which one?

242
00:12:55,733 --> 00:12:57,218
Porta Potti.

243
00:12:57,218 --> 00:12:59,915
Now I'm seeing it.

244
00:13:00,465 --> 00:13:02,772
Let's take a look.

245
00:13:08,799 --> 00:13:11,376
There's a real time capsule for you.

246
00:13:11,376 --> 00:13:14,428
35 years as a fish motel.

247
00:13:17,451 --> 00:13:20,627
What've you got there, Lil,
a dead fish?

248
00:13:20,627 --> 00:13:22,803
Or a wallet.

249
00:13:22,803 --> 00:13:25,085
I should be doing this in the lab.

250
00:13:25,085 --> 00:13:27,043
I won't tell on you, Louie.

251
00:13:27,043 --> 00:13:28,559
Want an Orange Crush?

252
00:13:28,559 --> 00:13:30,371
Yeah.

253
00:13:33,340 --> 00:13:38,679
So, Elisa you actually 
introduce people to.

254
00:13:38,679 --> 00:13:39,783
Sets her apart.

255
00:13:39,783 --> 00:13:41,210
Yeah.

256
00:13:41,210 --> 00:13:44,479
I'm sorry about that, uh, comment.

257
00:13:44,479 --> 00:13:46,261
I don't mind getting 
called beautiful.

258
00:13:46,261 --> 00:13:48,977
Well, she's not a hundred 
percent healthy.

259
00:13:50,430 --> 00:13:53,308
Doctor calls it a... 
