00:29:15,785 --> 00:29:19,704
But in retrospect, it was 
the right thing for me.

531
00:29:19,704 --> 00:29:24,416
Did you realize that 
before or after they died?

532
00:29:25,748 --> 00:29:29,406
Lil, Scotty, we got 
the FBI file on Jane.

533
00:29:29,406 --> 00:29:30,518
What, they had a file?

534
00:29:30,518 --> 00:29:32,078
And they gave it up?

535
00:29:32,078 --> 00:29:33,243
It's public record now.

536
00:29:33,243 --> 00:29:34,650
We get names of informants?

537
00:29:34,650 --> 00:29:36,512
No, they drew the line there, 
but we did get these.

538
00:29:36,512 --> 00:29:39,314
Yeah, surveillance photos 
of the Jane volunteers.

539
00:29:39,314 --> 00:29:42,745
Julia and Gerard, picking up 
and dropping off women

540
00:29:42,745 --> 00:29:44,860
April through June of '69.

541
00:29:44,860 --> 00:29:47,185
This your young Renee?

542
00:29:48,769 --> 00:29:49,450
That's her.

543
00:29:49,450 --> 00:29:52,302
Then this was the day they disappeared.

544
00:29:52,302 --> 00:29:53,798
Someone else was there.

545
00:29:53,798 --> 00:29:56,476
Someone who took these photos 
and gave them to the Feds.

546
00:29:56,476 --> 00:29:58,095
An informant.

547
00:29:58,095 --> 00:30:00,147
That nut case Lionel was right.

548
00:30:00,147 --> 00:30:03,603
Lionel thought Gerard was a snitch.

549
00:30:04,635 --> 00:30:07,876
Gerard didn't take these.

550
00:30:08,445 --> 00:30:10,819
So who did?

551
00:30:13,996 --> 00:30:15,571
Informants?

552
00:30:15,571 --> 00:30:16,893
Sound off the wall?

553
00:30:16,893 --> 00:30:18,823
Sounds dated.

554
00:30:18,823 --> 00:30:21,099
Our case is dated.

555
00:30:21,412 --> 00:30:23,998
There were always rumors like that.

556
00:30:23,998 --> 00:30:26,385
Looks like a parlor game at the commune,

557
00:30:26,385 --> 00:30:29,906
trying to decide who the snitch was.

558
00:30:29,906 --> 00:30:31,163
Weird.

559
00:30:31,163 --> 00:30:33,553
It was a paranoid time.

560
00:30:33,802 --> 00:30:37,343
Well, it seems there was 
someone watching Julia.

561
00:30:37,343 --> 00:30:39,760
Then I guess it wasn't paranoia.

562
00:30:39,760 --> 00:30:44,152
So in the parlor game, 
who'd you suspect?

563
00:30:44,734 --> 00:30:47,571
It wasn't a suspicion.

564
00:30:48,493 --> 00:30:50,967
Intuition?

565
00:30:52,132 --> 00:30:54,713
Adam and Julia were non-monogamous.

566
00:30:54,713 --> 00:30:56,690
He told us.

567
00:30:57,698 --> 00:31:00,177
And I...

568
00:31:00,577 --> 00:31:03,676
Had first-hand knowledge of that?

569
00:31:03,676 --> 00:31:05,712
Yes.

570
00:31:05,712 --> 00:31:10,064
Granted, I was sort of 
tripping at the time.

571
00:31:15,649 --> 00:31:17,851
It's so fragile.

572
00:31:19,492 --> 00:31:21,455
Can I take its picture?

573
00:31:35,947 --> 00:31:37,799
These are great.

574
00:31:38,224 --> 00:31:40,923
I'm documenting the movement.

575
00:31:40,923 --> 00:31:42,299
Yeah?

576
00:31:42,299 --> 00:31:44,560
I'm gonna do a book someday...

577
00:31:45,152 --> 00:31:47,610
tell the story.

578
00:31:48,332 --> 00:31:51,754
I love this one of Julia.

579
00:31:53,744 --> 00:31:55,690
Yeah.

580
00:31:55,690 --> 00:31:58,367
Have any of me?

581
00:31:59,109 --> 00:32:01,724
I'll take some right now.

582
00:32:05,617 --> 00:32:12,013
How about a rich Jersey girl 
beds penniless draft dodger.

583
00:32:13,060 --> 00:32:17,235
The camera was pretty 
sophisticated for a guy like him.

584
00:32:17,632 --> 00:32:23,749
It came into my mind for a 
second, but I was so flattered

585
00:32:23,749 --> 00:32:28,050
that he considered me part of 
the movement I put it out again.

586
00:32:28,317 --> 00:32:31,119
He ever put out that book?

587
00:32:34,866 --> 00:32:36,722
Boss, we got some.

588
00:32:36,722 --> 00:32:38,616
Yeah, us, too.

589
00:32:38,616 --> 00:32:43,075
Adam Clarke, burning his draft card in '69.

590
00:32:43,075 --> 00:32:44,556
He told us about that.

591
00:32:44,556 --> 00:32:47,135
Problem is, Adam shouldn't 
have had a draft card in '69.

592
00:32:47,135 --> 00:32:49,395
We checked his military records.
He's already served.

593
00:32:49,395 --> 00:32:51,685
Vietnam, '66 to '67.

594
00:32:51,685 --> 00:32:52,714
Really?

595
00:32:52,714 --> 00:32:55,240
When Adam gets home, 
it gets more interesting.

596
00:32:55,240 --> 00:32:59,399
He crossed state lines driving 
a "peace van" loaded with weed.

597
00:32:59,399 --> 00:33:01,940
Arrested for drug sales.

598
00:33:01,940 --> 00:33:04,255
Thought he was too 
disorganized for that.

599
00:33:04,255 --> 00:33:05,643
The case should have 
bought him state time.

600
00:33:05,643 --> 00:33:07,560
But then the feds took over 
jurisdiction.

601
00:33:07,560 --> 00:33:09,416
Poof. Case went away.

602
00:33:09,416 --> 00:33:10,988
He made a deal with them.

603
00:33:10,988 --> 00:33:12,833
Became a CI.

604
00:33:12,833 --> 00:33:14,709
"Stay in the movement, 
keep us informed."

605
00:33:14,709 --> 00:33:16,925
Now those photos he had 
of Julia really make sense.

606
00:33:16,925 --> 00:33:19,574
Black and White, long lens.

607
00:33:19,574 --> 00:33:24,220
Adam Clarke: '60s babe magnet,
star of the anti-war movement.

608
00:33:24,220 --> 00:33:26,655
And FBI informant.

609
00:33:26,655 --> 00:33:27,893
That'd be big news.

610
00:33:27,893 --> 00:33:28,893
Big, bad news.

611
00:33:28,893 --> 00:33:30,940
And if Julia found out?

612
00:33:30,940 --> 00:33:33,309
There's your motive for murder.

613
00:33:36,318 --> 00:33:38,537
Do you mind?

614
00:33:38,765 --> 00:33:40,670
Not at all.

615
00:33:52,130 --> 00:33:54,242
I know why you're here, Lilly.

616
00:33:54,876 --> 00:33:56,453
Yeah?

617
00:33:56,959 --> 00:34:01,007
I was an informant fot the FBI in 1969.

618
00:34:01,581 --> 00:34:03,087
Go on.

619
00:34:03,087 --> 00:34:05,431
My old case agent called.
Give me a heads up.

620
00:34:05,431 --> 00:34:07,939
Questions were being asked.

621
00:34:07,939 --> 00:34:10,871
They didn't give us name. / I know.

622
00:34:10,871 --> 00:34:14,658
And when you told me 
about Julia and Gerard,

623
00:34:14,658 --> 00:34:21,391
I... I hoped that my background 
was irrelevant, but...

624
00:34:22,514 --> 00:34:24,716
it may not be.

625
00:34:26,349 --> 00:34:31,017
I was surveilling them 
the day they disappeared.

626
00:34:32,629 --> 00:34:36,101
June 3, 1969.

627
00:34:36,101 --> 00:34:38,973
7:20 a.m.

628
00:34:38,973 --> 00:34:41,430
Yeah. This guy's name is 
Charlie Rinzler.

629
00:34:41,430 --> 00:34:42,892
I-I know who he is.

630
00:34:42,892 --> 00:34:44,577
Is-is that all you have of him?

631
00:34:44,577 --> 00:34:48,668
Oh, he was so agitated,
I reported it to my case agent.

632
00:34:48,668 --> 00:34:51,894
The Feds ran his license,
had me follow him for a week,

633
00:34:51,894 --> 00:34:54,246
but nothing much came of it.

634
00:34:54,550 --> 00:34:59,845
So, you have photos of Charlie from the 
week after Julia and Gerard went missing?

635
00:34:59,845 --> 00:35:03,056
Yeah, but nothing too exciting.

636
00:35:03,056 --> 00:35:05,606
Can I see them anyway?

637
00:35:06,682 --> 00:35:10,957
I basically followed him every 
day for a week to and from work.

638
00:35:10,957 --> 00:35:14,848
He was a day worker, in construction.

639
00:35:16,617 --> 00:35:18,973
Can I take these?

640
00:35:22,380 --> 00:35:24,193
They're yours...

641
00:35:24,193 --> 00:35:28,074
if I can ask a favor.

642
00:35:28,556 --> 00:35:32,931
If we can keep your secret, we will.

643
00:35:37,008 --> 00:35:40,098
You worked construction back 
in the 60s, huh, Charl?

644
00:35:40,098 --> 00:35:42,146
Yeah, couple of summers.

645
00:35:42,146 --> 00:35:44,389
Remember a job at the Calvin Building,

646
00:35:44,389 --> 00:35:45,390
summer of '69?

647
00:35:45,390 --> 00:35:47,311
Putting down the foundation?

648
00:35:47,311 --> 00:35:48,411
Maybe.

649
00:35:48,411 --> 00:35:51,435
'Cause that just happens to be 
where Julia and Gerard were dumped.

650
00:35:51,435 --> 00:35:53,542
The same week you worked there.

651
00:35:53,542 --> 00:35:54,508
It's an amazing coincidence.

652
00:35:54,508 --> 00:35:56,877
Mm, too amazing.

653
00:35:57,215 --> 00:36:00,017
That-that can't be right.

654
00:36:00,448 --> 00:36:04,127
This is you at the 
construction site, Charlie.

655
00:36:04,730 --> 00:36:07,054
- Who the hell took that?
- Good luck you had.

656
00:36:07,054 --> 00:36:08,586
That foundation was being laid

657
00:36:08,586 --> 00:36:10,545
just when you needed to 
stash two dead hippies.

658
00:36:10,545 --> 00:36:12,708
I never hurt them.

659
00:36:14,916 --> 00:36:16,374
That guy was nice to me.

660
00:36:16,374 --> 00:36:19,636
Long as that building was up,
you figured you were home free.

661
00:36:19,936 --> 00:36:22,825
Too bad they want 
a parking lot there now.

662
00:36:22,825 --> 00:36:24,588
It's coincidence.

663
00:36:24,588 --> 00:36:26,852
That's all.

664
00:36:31,364 --> 00:36:33,937
I guess I need a lawyer.

665
00:36:35,534 --> 00:36:37,570
Update for you.

666
00:36:42,394 --> 00:36:45,270
Forensics is back on the 
hair found with the bodies.

667
00:36:45,270 --> 00:36:46,716
And?

668
00:36:47,054 --> 00:36:48,192
It ain't Julia's.

669
00:36:48,192 --> 00:36:51,545
So, there was someone else
at the scene with long, brown hair.

670
00:36:51,545 --> 00:36:52,352
Charlie?

671
00:36:52,352 --> 00:36:53,458
He was Nixon youth.

672
00:36:53,458 --> 00:36:54,616
Crew cut.

673
00:36:54,616 --> 00:36:57,106
How about Adam Clarke?

674
00:36:57,106 --> 00:36:57,815
Long.

675
00:36:57,815 --> 00:36:59,888
Yeah, but a lot of people 
had long hair back then.

676
00:36:59,888 --> 00:37:02,185
And Adam came clean 
about being an informant.

677
00:37:02,185 --> 00:37:03,621
FBI wasn't gonna confirm.

678
00:37:03,621 --> 00:37:05,865
Put himself in harm's way.

679
00:37:05,865 --> 00:37:09,427
Unless he practices what he preaches.

680
00:37:12,319 --> 00:37:16,087
"People who win face the real facts
of whatever situation they're in."

681
00:37:16,087 --> 00:37:17,849
Maybe he looked at the odds,

682
00:37:17,849 --> 00:37:20,911
knew we'd make him as the informant,
with or without confirmation.

683
00:37:20,911 --> 00:37:22,975
So he steps out ahead of us.

684
00:37:22,975 --> 00:37:24,449
Make himself look good.

685
00:37:24,449 --> 00:37:26,123
And sets up Charlie.

686
00:37:26,666 --> 00:37:30,560
"Audacious action, with the element of 
surprise, will give you the upper hand."

687
00:37:30,560 --> 00:37:32,708
We know Adam followed 
Charlie around for a week.

688
00:37:32,708 --> 00:37:34,088
He saw where he worked.

689
00:37:34,088 --> 00:37:35,677
Could've dumped the 
bodies there one night.

690
00:37:35,677 --> 00:37:38,707
Which points right to Charlie 
if anything ever comes to light.

691
00:37:38,707 --> 00:37:41,836
And Adam gets 35 years
to have a life...

692
00:37:42,036 --> 00:37:43,497
till his luck runs out.

693
00:37:43,497 --> 00:37:45,179
We got enough to compel a DNA sample?

694
00:37:45,179 --> 00:37:47,521
I mean, this guy ain't gonna give it up.

695
00:37:47,521 --> 00:37:49,809
He already did.

696
00:37:54,420 --> 00:37:57,214
Those pictures, 
they were real helpful, Adam.

697
00:37:57,430 --> 00:37:58,309
I'm glad.

698
00:37:58,309 --> 00:38:00,142
You're an excellent photographer.

699
00:38:00,142 --> 00:38:02,155
Composition, framing...

700
00:38:02,155 --> 00:38:04,032
Especially framing.

701
00:38:04,277 --> 00:38:05,858
How'd it go down, anyway?

702
00:38:05,858 --> 00:38:09,091
You get sloppy that day, 
Julia and Gerard catch you?

703
00:38:09,091 --> 00:38:11,656
I... don't follow.

704
00:38:11,656 --> 00:38:13,448
Charlie didn't kill them.

705
00:38:13,448 --> 00:38:14,568
Good try, though.

706
00:38:14,568 --> 00:38:16,508
I never said he did.

707
00:38:16,508 --> 00:38:22,289
Adam Clarke -- 
real hippie or... poser?

708
00:38:22,289 --> 00:38:23,689
Real.

709
00:38:23,689 --> 00:38:26,581
My passions were very real.

710
00:38:27,106 --> 00:38:29,327
How'd you like having long hair?

711
00:38:29,327 --> 00:38:31,445
All them strands blowing around.

712
00:38:31,445 --> 00:38:32,856
And guess what, Adam?

713
00:38:32,856 --> 00:38:36,995
One of them blew right into the plastic
bags you wrapped your friends in.

714
00:38:36,995 --> 00:38:38,833
Got stuck under the tape.

715
00:38:38,833 --> 00:38:41,839
A long, brown hair that don't 
belong to either of them.

716
00:38:41,839 --> 00:38:46,113
You think I was the only guy with long 
hair those two were in contact with?

717
00:38:46,113 --> 00:38:50,139
Well, the DNA on this will confirm it.

718
00:38:51,322 --> 00:38:54,492
Whether you were a real 
hippie or not doesn't matter.

719
00:38:54,492 --> 00:38:56,992
Your long hair got you in the end.

720
00:38:56,992 --> 00:38:58,778
Why'd you do it Adam?

721
00:38:58,778 --> 00:39:02,034
Were you against 
what "Jane" was doing?

722
00:39:02,996 --> 00:39:05,708
I thought they were heroic.

723
00:39:06,608 --> 00:39:10,249
I didn't want Julia or 
Gerard to be harmed.

724
00:39:10,249 --> 00:39:12,922
But then they found out about you.

725
00:39:12,922 --> 00:39:17,479
Pretty soon the whole movement would 
know you were a snitch for the FBI.

726
00:39:18,168 --> 00:39:20,283
The Feds had me.

727
00:39:20,707 --> 00:39:22,019
I had no options.

728
00:39:22,019 --> 00:39:24,924
How about taking responsibility?

729
00:39:25,195 --> 00:39:27,771
Ain't that the winner's way?

730
00:39:27,771 --> 00:39:31,184
I was a leader in the revolution.

731
00:39:31,982 --> 00:39:35,052
We were living like it meant something.

732
00:39:36,793 --> 00:39:39,281
I loved that life.

733
00:39:40,092 --> 00:39:42,585
Couldn't stand to give it up.

734
00:39:42,585 --> 00:39:46,113
Ever wonder if Julia 
and Gerard felt that way?

735
00:39:46,662 --> 00:39:49,267
Think they loved their lives?

736
00:40:31,955 --> 00:40:33,339
Hey, Jules.

737
00:40:33,339 --> 00:40:35,036
Gerard.

738
00:40:36,682 --> 00:40:37,914
What are you guys doing here?

739
00:40:37,914 --> 00:40:39,278
What's going on, Adam?

740
00:40:39,278 --> 00:40:41,067
You taking our pictures?

741
00:40:41,067 --> 00:40:42,675
I'm always taking pictures.

742
00:40:42,675 --> 00:40:46,208
Yeah, what 8:00 in the morning, 
on a deserted corner?

743
00:40:46,208 --> 00:40:48,478
I-I don't get this.

744
00:40:49,671 --> 00:40:51,800
Oh, man.

745
00:40:52,100 --> 00:40:54,225
This is sad.

746
00:40:54,475 --> 00:40:55,736
He's a snitch.

747
00:40:55,736 --> 00:40:57,049
Come on, Adam Clarke?

748
00:40:57,049 --> 00:40:59,011
Who better?

749
00:40:59,364 --> 00:41:02,087
This is crazy, right?

750
00:41:04,129 --> 00:41:05,823
Let's...

751
00:41:05,823 --> 00:41:07,641
Let's get in the car. / Adam.

752
00:41:07,641 --> 00:41:09,068
Just do it, Jules.

